Each workshop prompted a high level of debate. Participants clearly engaged with the materials being presented and, later, were able to identify ways in which they could promote the resources within their own organisations.

Following the workshops, we were approached to deliver training in Australia to two child care providers, to facilitate a number of peer support groups and to offer further advice to those setting up and running their own workshops.</gtr:impact><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Professional Practitioners</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:year>2014</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Reflective Workshop (Wesley Mission, Melbourne, Australia)</gtr:description><gtr:form>A talk or presentation</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>International</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>1B187E43-AB67-4DFF-A6FB-CE341AABE3E2</gtr:id><gtr:impact>Wesley Mission are a national children's agency in Australia who provide a range of services to vulnerable children and their families. A selection of residential workers from across the state of Victoria attended a Reflective Workshop in May 2014. The materials presented generated robust discussion with participants readily applying the key concepts of Food for Thought to practice examples. The evaluation of the training highlighted the powerful impact it had had in relation to reflecting on practice, raising awareness of the symbolic nature of food and the need to better take account of how children might be using food to communicate and to build/test relationships.

