tr:description><gtr:end>2017-06-02</gtr:end><gtr:fundingOrg>Economic and Social Research Council (ESRC)</gtr:fundingOrg><gtr:id>76C8F82E-375B-48DF-A0DE-CA7A3998FD25</gtr:id><gtr:sector>Public</gtr:sector><gtr:start>2014-10-01</gtr:start></gtr:furtherFundingOutput><gtr:furtherFundingOutput><gtr:amountPounds>29364</gtr:amountPounds><gtr:country>United States of America</gtr:country><gtr:currCode>EUR</gtr:currCode><gtr:currCountryCode>Austria</gtr:currCountryCode><gtr:currLang>de_AT</gtr:currLang><gtr:description>Post Doctoral Fellowship</gtr:description><gtr:end>2015-07-02</gtr:end><gtr:fundingOrg>German Academic Exchange Service (DAAD)</gtr:fundingOrg><gtr:id>1CF62F5D-63D2-4F2A-A3B2-68B31AF0971F</gtr:id><gtr:sector>Public</gtr:sector><gtr:start>2014-09-01</gtr:start></gtr:furtherFundingOutput></gtr:furtherFundingOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutput><gtr:description>Narrative Impact Report Food for Thought Project 
Ref number: ES/J020745/1


Food for Thought (FFT) was a knowledge exchange project which aimed to generate, deliver and sustain a range of resources relating to the symbolic use of food and food practices in foster and residential care. Data originally drawn from a previous ESRC funded project (Food Practices in an Institutional Context: Children, Care and Control, Ref number: RES-000-23-1581) formed the basis for the resources. These were devised and piloted with three agency partners (Perth and Kinross Council, Aberlour Child Care Trust and Foster Care Associates), all of which provided residential and/or foster care services to children in Scotland. 

The project added to the knowledge base and skill set of both residential and foster carers, as well as their managers and supervising social workers. These developments not only related to food based practices, but extended to promote understanding of the ways in which adults and children communicate through symbolic means. The resources targeted aspects of direct care and aimed to improve practice effectiveness as well as, in turn, enhance the quality of life of looked after children and young people. 

One key element of the project was the sustainability of the practice resources. To this end, materials are not only freely available to individuals and organisations on the project website (www.foodforthoughtproject.info) but they also include guidance for those wishing to deliver face to face training or to facilitate peer support groups. Furthermore, partnerships with IRISS (Institute for Research and Innovation in the Social Services) and CELCIS (Centre for Excellence in Looked After Children in Scotland) have ensured that the resources and materials devised in this year long project will remain in the public domain. IRISS will continue to service the project website whilst CELCIS have embedded aspects of the project into their teaching on the MSc in Advanced Residential Child Care. 

The project's practice-based resources and training workshops for practitioners, trainers and research managers have been delivered at local, national and international levels. The project outputs have already informed policy and practice in eight local authorities in Scotland, in five centres in the south of England and in one organisation in Australia. This impact funding enabled us to advance knowledge exchange between academics, practitioners, carers and educators in relation to food practices and child care nationally, within the wider UK and internationally (leading to links with child care organisations and universities in Finland, Germany and Australia). The growing impact from this project means that it has been identified as a key Impact Case Study for REF2020 for the School of Applied Social Science at the University of Stirling.

Summary of how findings are being used
Since the launch of FFT in November 2013, we are aware that a number of organisations have and continue to use the training and resources produced by the Food for Thought project. For example, Perth and Kinross Council have incorporated FFT materials into their induction training for new foster carers, The Scottish Residential Child Care Workers Association have run FFT peer support groups and Berry Street (a childcare organisation in Melbourne, Australia) are using the FFT Reflective Workshops as part of mandatory induction training for all their residential staff. Reflective workshops have also been delivered in house by one large NHS authority (NHS Lothian) and by Foster Care Associates in four of their regional areas in Scotland. 

The FFT academic team have continued to support the use of the resources in practice. For example, a wide range of practitioners, foster carers and managers attended the four Train the Trainer workshops held at the University of Stirling. These included representatives from across the UK (e.g. Dundee City Council, Snowdon Residential School, Foster Plus, North Lanarkshire Council, West Lothian Council, Glasgow Simon Community, Edinburgh City Council, Harmeny Residential School, Integrated Services Programme [Kent and the Southeast]). These workshops aimed to increase confidence in those looking to deliver FFT workshops in their organisations. We have had on going contact with a number of these participants who are looking to, or have, integrated FFT into their training for staff and carers as well as their day to day practice. We have also facilitated seven peer support sessions in a wide range of settings and organisations and delivered an additional three reflective workshops. We have received requests to deliver workshops in Liverpool and in Fife and plan to run these in the early autumn 2015. 

To date, the FFT team has collected data on the initial impact of attending reflective workshops and peer support groups (approx. 170 foster carers and practitioners). The vast majority of participants ranked the materials highly or extremely relevant to their care of children. Many identified areas of practice that they would do differently as a result of attending the sessions. These included: reviewing how they managed mealtimes, greater flexibility around routines, thinking about what the child might be telling them through their use of food, considering how they might use food to let children know that they care about them. Interestingly, participants also identified issues that they would want to discuss further in supervision or in subsequent peer support meetings. The following quotes from evaluation forms and interviews are typical:

I found the training day really informative. It's probably one of the best training days I've been to for a long time it really opened my eyes to how we used food in Residential Care I want all the staff to go on the training (Residential Manager)

At the training session they did say it would make us question our habits as adults, not just the children, our rules, our priorities and such like and it has done that! (Foster Carer). 

I think it's been really positive. I've had carers come up and say 'you've been involved in that [FFT] and what was it like, what's it all about' and . It seems people are really interested (Foster Carer)

Evolution of the project
The project has grown in a range of ways since the end of the funding period. Whilst as stated above, there continues to be growth in demand for FFT team to facilitate workshops and peer support groups we also have an increase in numbers of organisations delivering the reflective workshops themselves. This is an indicator of the resources becoming more embedded in the practice community and 'ownership' transferring from the FFT team to practice. In line with this, we have been approached by two agencies (NHS Lothian and FCA) who would like us to bring together organisations who are using the FFT materials. They are keen to look at ways to consolidate and build on the work of the project and to learn from each other. It is planned that the first of these meetings will take place in October 2015. 

The demand to establish an ongoing network around FFT has been replicated in the experiences of members of the steering group. Importantly, whilst the project funding ended in May 2014, the steering group has continued to meet on a quarterly basis. This group continues to share information about 'best practice', lessons learned from using FFT resources and strategies to improve direct care practice. The group has exchanged knowledge about wider policy and practice initiatives and have looked to the group for support and advice. 

Although it was a knowledge exchange project, the team also undertook empirical research exploring the experience of partnership working, co-production and knowledge exchange. This work has shed light on factors which contribute to sustained partnerships and the embedding of research into policy and practice. Two refereed journals articles are being prepared to present the findings from this aspect of the study. In addition, funding was secured from the Scottish Graduate School Doctoral Training Centre for a PhD studentship which will critically examine knowledge exchange and research impact using FFT as a case study. As part of this, follow up data concerning the use of FFT resources and their direct impact on practice will be gathered over a further three year period (including PhD fieldwork in Australia) in order to chart the international impact journey which began in Melbourne with colleagues from Deakin University. This international link has also led to the joint writing of a journal article with Helen Skouteris, Professor in Developmental Psychology and Dr Rachael Cox at Deakin University, Melbourne: &amp;quot;Day-to-day food practices and physical activity routines in residential care: 'The odds are against you'&amp;quot; as well as to a joint National Health and Medical Research Council grant application which is in preparation and will combine FFT with their &amp;quot;Healthy Eating &amp;amp; Active Living&amp;quot; HEAL project

We have been surprised by the international interest in the FFT resources. Information gathered from the project website indicates that the resources have been downloaded and have attracted attention from across the world. As of March 2015 there have been over 4,000 page views, including 2605 downloads of our resources. The staff handbook, children's leaflet, reflective tool and peer support guidance have been translated into Finnish and in addition, we have been invited to facilitate FFT workshops in Australia and Germany as well as had requests to present on the materials in Ireland, England and across Scotland.

Challenges to achieve impact 

The project faced a number of challenges to achieving impact. They included the following:
1. Staff and carers reported feeling 'overwhelmed' by training and policy initiatives. In the development workshops that we ran at the start of the project, they also stated that they found it hard to make links between all the different training they had received. Finally, many described difficulties in applying new knowledge to practice. The FFT team overcame these difficulties by creating a suite of resources for staff and carers that targeted a range of learning styles and which allowed staff and carers to be in control of the pace and volume of knowledge. Many of the resources refer to other key training (e.g. attachment theory, relationship based practice) and how FFT connects to these other arenas of practice knowledge. Finally, the team provided a range of tools that could be used in practice to support knowledge transfer (e.g. the Reflective Tool). 

2. A number of partner agencies reported pressure of work and that this restricted or made their involvement more challenging. To overcome this, we offered to facilitate peer support groups and to meet with senior managers to help embed FFT and to support agency representatives in their quest to do this. Agency partners used some of the steering group time to discuss strategies they had employed within their organisations (for example in house 'steering groups' as well as devising a FFT implementation plan). These tools were also shared with other organisational representatives. 

3. Project funding was available for one year only. This resulted in limited opportunities to robustly assess and analyse impact. To overcome this we have been able to secure full funding for a three year PhD studentship which will look critically at impact using FFT as a case study. We have also embedded basic data capture techniques into the website to allow us to track numbers of visits to the site and the number of resources that were downloaded. A number of agencies who have employed FFT resources have committed to feeding back evaluation data and have put in place ways to track the use of FFT materials in their organisation (for example FCA have developed a FFT learning and activities log which tracks all FFT related activities, evaluations and reported impacts).</gtr:description><gtr:firstYearOfImpact>2013</gtr:firstYearOfImpact><gtr:id>DF9249DD-3A53-4A78-8B5C-02D188862974</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes><gtr:impactType>Cultural,Societal</gtr:impactType></gtr:impactTypes><gtr:sector>Agriculture, Food and Drink,Communities and Social Services/Policy,Education,Healthcare</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>Working closely in partnership with three care providers (Aberlour Childcare Trust, Foster Care Associates and Perth &amp;amp; Kinross Council) and two national institutions (CELCIS - Centre for Excellence for Looked After Children in Scotland and IRISS-Institute for Research and Innovation in Social Services), the Food for Thought project built on data produced in our ESRC funded study of food practices in residential care. The partnership co-produced a series of resources which translated, applied and developed this previous data in ways which appear, from initial feedback, to have been relevant, useful and sustainable to residential practitioners and foster carers of looked after children. Resources were developed in face to face monthly meetings with partners and during development workshops involving residential and foster carers. 
During this co-production process it became clear that the three resources outlined by the partnership in the initial funding application could be adapted. In workshops, carers and staff described their experience of being overwhelmed by the volume of stand-alone training they had attended, the often generic content of training materials and their desire not just to be taught but to learn. Consequently, the Food for Thought group worked together to produce five key resources catering for different learning styles which aimed not only to provide information about food based practice but also opportunities for reflection, application and links to other training and learning. 
The Resources
An interactive, activity based Reflective Workshop (with a Facilitators' Pack including all support materials) was created to raise awareness of the symbolic use of food in care settings and to provide opportunities for participants to share reflections and practices. An Online Interactive Introduction was devised for individuals or staff groups to introduce or revisit core Food for Thought concepts. Responding to carers' concerns that training can often be too 'abstract' and disconnected from day to day practice, we developed three resources which helped them to focus on the individual children or the food based issues currently being faced (Reflective Tool, JOTIT Notebook and Peer Support Guidance). These resources support reflection and analysis of individual children or food related concerns and provide a mechanism whereby issues can be recorded, brought to supervision or discussed in a peer support forum. In addition, we produced a short monograph summarising wider academic research on children, food and care. 
All the resources are free to download from our website www.foodforthoughtproject.info
It would appear that the co-production and take up of these resources has gone some way to meeting our three key conceptual, instrumental and capacity building objectives: to promote awareness and understanding of the symbolic use of food; to equip foster carers and residential staff with the knowledge, skills and resources to observe and understand children's food practices; and to facilitate staff/carers' reflections on their own food related interventions and how these might be maximised to therapeutic ends. 
As part of the project, the challenging process of developing with rather than for carers and practitioners was evaluated by conducting interviews with all partners and carers involved in the design and piloting of the resources. What was striking was the centrality of relationships to the experience of participation and indeed to the success of the project. Participants described a genuine sense of ownership of the materials, passion and enthusiasm for the subject matter and a desire to promote and maintain the use of the resources within their own, and other, organisations. 
We continue to receive much interest in the resources from a range of service providers, including those providing care to adults. We are keen to extend our work to residential care for older people.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>The project has attracted significant attention from researchers across the UK and internationally. A number of our resources have been translated into German and Finnish and we have provided workshop training sessions to colleagues in Australia. The partnership will continue to promote the resources as well as disseminate findings relating to co- production and partnership working. We are currently writing two academic journal articles on data relating to knowledge exchange and co-production. All partners have also committed to, and set up, an evaluation of the uptake and use of the resources over a five year period. The data generated through this evaluation, as well as our impact strategy, will be reported in two practice based articles. 
The project launch at Stirling University involved 90 practitioners, academics and policy makers. This led to take up of the resources by a care provider in England (ISP) as well as an invitation to present to the 150 members of the Scottish Care Inspectorate. We have presented to academic audiences in Germany (Eichst&amp;auml;tt and Vechta), Australia, Ireland, England and Scotland and have planned future events including presenting at an international conference (BAPSCAN 2015). Our project Briefing has been sent to our research database, as well as distributed via CELCIS, IRISS and the Centre for Research on Families and Relationships.
Academics within the social studies of childhood, alternative care for children and the sociology of food have shown interest in how we have translated our findings to practice. For example, colleagues working with the HEAL project (Deakin University, Melbourne) drew on our project to explore the process of engaging staff and in the co-production of research based practice tools. They have asked that Food for Thought materials be translated into an online training module which will form part of a course they are producing aimed at residential staff in Australia.
Our conceptual work and resources have also been used in undergraduate and postgraduate teaching at Stirling University and in the training of residential and social work staff, such as the MSc Advanced Residential Child Care at the University of Strathclyde. 
(word count 346)
 
The resources developed by the FFT team have also been taken forward by a number of practice and child care organisations. This encompasses adult providers of care (residential staff, foster/adoptive parents/carers, supervising social workers and managers) as well as children (those looked after away from home, with physical or learning disabilities or with emotional and behavioural difficulties). 
Food for Thought has already impacted on how staff and carers understand and respond to the food practices of children in their care. This has been demonstrated in workshop evaluation forms, feedback from partner agencies and spontaneous contact from staff and carers. They describe feeling more confident in reflecting on food based behaviours, more aware of the symbolic meaning of food and of it's the therapeutic potential.
In order to support practice staff to run Reflective Workshops within their organisations, we delivered three Train the Trainer events (totalling 50 trainers from across Scotland and 10 from Germany, Australia and England). In addition, we have been invited to facilitate six Peer Support Groups and to run two further Reflective Workshops. These activities have an economic impact (staff facilitate their own workshops rather than paying for external training) and a societal impact (staff and carers already report a change in direct practice and improved awareness of behaviours around food). 
We anticipate that these carers and practitioners will continue to promote the concepts underpinning Food for Thought and will be committed to shifting cultures of care around food. By providing a triangular model of knowledge exchange (group learning through Reflective Workshops, individual reflection/assessment using the Reflective Tool, and group discussion and problem solving using the Peer Support Model) we argue that Food for Thought is becoming a self-sustaining cycle of practice. We anticipate that once established in organisations, new staff or carers will be inducted into this approach and that, as a result, the quality of care for children and support given to staff will improve. As one participant stated: 'I found the session extremely helpful in providing clarity of thought and in highlighting the importance the role of food practices has in residential care'.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>394D1703-85A0-4FEA-996C-BDFE969BAD86</gtr:id><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Agriculture, Food and Drink,Communities and Social Services/Policy,Education,Healthcare</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors><gtr:url>http://www.foodforthoughtproject.info</gtr:url></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs><gtr:policyInfluenceOutput><gtr:areas/><gtr:description>MSc Social Work Studies (Stirling)</gtr:description><gtr:geographicReach>National</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>3C55BA72-D203-443B-8B50-E50CD65DCE0C</gtr:id><gtr:impact>Food for Thought is delivered to social workers in training on the MSc Social Work at the University of Stirling. Students are attracted from across the UK to register on this course. Many of the student continue to work in practice (most often in residential settings for children, older people and people with learning disabilities). A significant number experience practice learning placements in such settings. Four students have go on to request additional copies of the staff handbook and have reported changes in practice as a res